The Local Government Ordinance 2001], and was subdivided into 11 [[Union councils of Pakistan|Union Councils]]. The Town system and was disbanded in 2011,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribe.com/2011/07/11/karachi%e2%80%99s-district-status-restored-notification-issued/|title=Karachi\u2019s district status restored, notification issued|last=Abbasi|first=Saeed|date=2011-07-10|website=The News Tribe|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and Liaquatabad Town was re-organized as part of [[Karachi Central|Karachi Central District]] in 2015\n\n== History ==\nThe federal government under [[Pervez Musharraf]], who seized power in a [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|1999 coup d'etat]], introduced local government reforms in the year 2000, which eliminated the previous \"third tier of government\" ([[Divisions of Pakistan|administrative divisions]]) and replaced it with the fourth tier ([[Districts of Pakistan|districts]]). The effect in Karachi was the dissolution of the former [[Karachi Division]] in 2001, and the merging of its five districts to form a new Karachi City-District with eighteen autonomous constituent towns including Liaquatabad Town. In 2011, the system was disbanded but remained in place for bureaucratic administration until 2015, when the [[Karachi Metropolitan Corporation]] system was reintroduced. In 2015, Liaquatabad Town was re-organized as part of [[District of Central Karachi|Karachi Central]] district.\n\n== Neighbourhoods ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Abbasi Shaheed]]\n* [[Bandhani Colony]]\n* [[Commercial Area]]\n* [[Dak Khana]]\n* [[Firdous Colony]]\n* [[Mujahid Colony]]\n* [[Tughlaqabad (Karachi)|Tughlaqabad]]\n* [[Liaquatabad]]\n* [[Nazimabad]]\n* [[Qasimabad (Karachi)|Qasimabad]]\n* [[Rizvia Society|Rizvia Society (R.C.H.S.)]] (Rizvia Co-operative Housing Society)\n* [[Sharifabad (Karachi)|Sharifabad]]\n* [[Gharibabad]]\n* [[Super Market (Karachi)|Super Market]]\n* [[Khamosh Colony]]\n* [[Gulbahar]]\n* [[Teen Hatti]]\n* 