11111/http://www.karachicity.gov.pk/town/index.asp?txtTown=Liaquatabad Liaquatabad Town]\n\n{{Karachi Towns}}\n{{Karachi topics}}\n\n[[Category:Liaquatabad Town| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copy editing.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liaquatabad_Town"}
{"title_page": "American School of Dubai", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = The American School of Dubai aahan\n| logo =\n| motto = Every Student. Future Ready.\n| city = Dubai\n| country = United Arab Emirates\n| type = Non-profit\n| established = 1966\n| locale = Dubai, United Arab Emirates\n| head = Dr. Paul Richards\n| faculty = 300\n| athletics = Volleyball, Basketball, Soccer, Badminton, Track and Field, Cross Country, Swimming, Softball, Baseball, Golf, Wrestling, Tennis, with additional competition in Academic Games, Debate and Forensics.  Other intramural sports are also present. \n| mascot = Safwan the Aahan\n| website = {{url|http://www.asdubai.org}}\n| head_name = Superintendent\n| students = 1900\n| school_colors = red and white\n}}\nThe '''American School of Dubai''' ('''ASD''') is an independent, not-for-profit, U.S. curriculum, Pre-K through Grade 12 international school offering an American education. The school was founded in 1966 and was previously known as the '''Jumeirah American School (JAS)''', is now located in the Al-Barsha community of [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asdubai.org/page.cfm?p=513|title=American School of Dubai: At a Glance|website=www.asdubai.org|access-date=2019-05-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018-2019 ASD won awards for sustainability efforts. Most notably the Zayad Sustainability Prize (ZPS), Global High School Category (MENA Region) Award 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/winners-of-2019-zayed-sustainability-prize-announced-1.813085 |accessdate=15 Sept 2019 |language=en </ref>and 2020 Expo, 2018 Sustainability Champions Competition <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/over-100-schools-take-part-in-expo-2020-s-sustainability-champions-programme-2018-04-24-1.668519 |accessdate=15 Sept 2019 |language=en </ref>. Additional awards include Knowledge Review Magazine's, 10 Best International Schools in Dubai 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theknowledgereview.com/the-10-best-international-schools-in-dubai-2018-december2018/ |accessdate=15 Sept 2019 |language=en </ref>; Winner of the SchoolsCompared.com, Best American Curriculum School of the Year 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schoolscompared.com/guides/the-top-schools-in-the-uae-2019/ |accessdate=15 Sept 2019 |language=en </ref>.\n\nAround 2008, the school was reviewed by the ''[[Good Schools Guide International]]'' as \"One of the best thought-of and long established schools in Dubai\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsgi.cogapp.com/countries/united-arab-emirates/dubai/dubai-schools-considered-by-expats |title=American School of Dubai |accessdate=2008-09-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404075546/http://www.gsgi.cogapp.com/countries/united-arab-emirates/dubai/dubai-schools-considered-by-expats |archivedate=2009-04-04 |work=Good Schools Guide }}</ref> It was also rated by UAE based schools review web site, WhichSchoolAdvisor.com as one of the best schools in Dubai in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Westley |first1=David |title=Best Schools in Dubai - And Why |url=https://whichschooladvisor.com/uae/guides/the-best-schools-dubai-khda |website=whichschooladvisor.com |accessdate=22 May 2019 |language=en |date=June 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Knowledge and Human Development Authority]] (KHDA) rated the school as \"Good\" for the academic years 2008 through to the latest 2019 report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://whichschooladvisor.com/uae/school-review/american-school-of-dubai/inspection-report|title=American School of Dubai Inspection Report|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.asdubai.org/ American School of Dubai]\n*[http://www.dubaifaqs.com/american-school-of-dubai.php Information] on dubaifaqs.com\n*\n*\n{{coord|25|13|6|N|55|15|35|E|type:edu_region:AE|display=title}}\n\n{{International schools in the United Arab Emirates}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:American School Of Dubai}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Dubai]]\n[[Category:American international schools in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:American international schools]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1966]]\n[[Category:International schools in Dubai]]\n[[Category:Private schools in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:International schools in the United Arab Emirates]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = The American School of Dubai\n| logo =\n| motto = Every Student. Future Ready.\n| city = Dubai\n| country = United Arab Emirates\n| type = Non-profit\n| established = 1966\n| locale = Dubai, United Arab Emirates\n| head = Dr. Paul Richards\n| faculty = 300\n| athletics = Volleyball, Basketball, Soccer, Badminton, Track and Field, Cross Country, Swimming, Softball, Baseball, Golf, Wrestling, Tennis, with additional competition in Academic Games, Debate and Forensics.  Other intramural sports are also present. \n| mascot = Safwan the Aahan\n| website = {{url|http://www.asdubai.org}}\n| head_name = Superintendent\n| students = 1900\n| school_colors = red and white\n}}\nThe '''American School of Dubai''' ('''ASD''') is an independent, not-for-profit, U.S. curriculum, Pre-K through Grade 12 international school offering an American education. The school was founded in 1966 and was previously known as the '''Jumeirah American School (JAS)''', is now located in the Al-Barsha community of [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asdubai.org/page.cfm?p=513|title=American School of Dubai: At a Glance|website=www.asdubai.org|access-date=2019-05-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018-2019 ASD won awards for sustainability efforts. Most notably the Zayad Sustainability Prize (ZPS), Global High School Category (MENA Region) Award 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/winners-of-2019-zayed-sustainability-prize-announced-1.813085 |accessdate=15 Sept 2019 |language=en </ref>and 2020 Expo, 2018 Sustainability Champions Competition <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/over-100-schools-take-part-in-expo-2020-s-sustainability-champions-programme-2018-04-24-1.668519 |accessdate=15 Sept 2019 |language=en </ref>. Additional awards include Knowledge Review Magazine's, 10 Best International Schools in Dubai 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theknowledgereview.com/the-10-best-international-schools-in-dubai-2018-december2018/ |accessdate=15 Sept 2019 |language=en </ref>; Winner of the SchoolsCompared.com, Best American Curriculum School of the Year 2019 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schoolscompared.com/guides/the-top-schools-in-the-uae-2019/ |accessdate=15 Sept 2019 |language=en </ref>.\n\nAround 2008, the school was reviewed by the ''[[Good Schools Guide International]]'' as \"One of the best thought-of and long established schools in Dubai\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsgi.cogapp.com/countries/united-arab-emirates/dubai/dubai-schools-considered-by-expats |title=American School of Dubai |accessdate=2008-09-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404075546/http://www.gsgi.cogapp.com/countries/united-arab-emirates/dubai/dubai-schools-considered-by-expats |archivedate=2009-04-04 |work=Good Schools Guide }}</ref> It was also rated by UAE based schools review web site, WhichSchoolAdvisor.com as one of the best schools in Dubai in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Westley |first1=David |title=Best Schools in Dubai - And Why |url=https://whichschooladvisor.com/uae/guides/the-best-schools-dubai-khda |website=whichschooladvisor.com |accessdate=22 May 2019 |language=en |date=June 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Knowledge and Human Development Authority]] (KHDA) rated the school as \"Good\" for the academic years 2008 through to the latest 2019 report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://whichschooladvisor.com/uae/school-review/american-school-of-dubai/inspection-report|title=American School of Dubai Inspection Report|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.asdubai.org/ American School of Dubai]\n*[http://www.dubaifaqs.com/american-school-of-dubai.php Information] on dubaifaqs.com\n*\n*\n{{coord|25|13|6|N|55|15|35|E|type:edu_region:AE|display=title}}\n\n{{International schools in the United Arab Emirates}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:American School Of Dubai}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Dubai]]\n[[Category:American international schools in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:American international schools]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1966]]\n[[Category:International schools in Dubai]]\n[[Category:Private schools in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:International schools in the United Arab Emirates]]\n", "name_user": "Jackjohnssonn", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_School_of_Dubai"}
{"title_page": "1987 in literature", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|1987|literature|poetry}}\n\nThis article presents lists of the literary events and publications of '''1987'''.\n<!-- Redlinks will be removed. They make no sense in a list. Add pages as you write them. -->\n==Events==\n*[[January 2]] \u2013 [[Golliwog]]s in [[Enid Blyton]] children's books are replaced by the British publisher with [[gnome]]s after complaints of a racial offence implication.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://static.expressandstar.com/days/1976-2000/1987.html |title=1987 |work=Those were the days |publisher=Express & Star |location=Wolverhampton |accessdate=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n*April \u2013 [[K. W. Jeter]] coins the term \"[[Steampunk]]\" in a letter published in ''[[Locus (magazine)|Locus: the magazine of the science fiction & fantasy field]]''.\n*June \u2013 [[Virago Press]] of London publishes ''Down the Road, Worlds Away'', a collection of short stories ostensibly by Rahila Khan, a young Muslim woman living in England. Three weeks later, Toby Forward, an Anglican clergyman, admits to writing them and the publisher withdraws the book. \"He, unlike the editors at Virago, had grown up in precisely the kind of area and social conditions that the book described.... Although the book never claimed to be other than a work of fiction, the publishers destroyed the stock still in the warehouse and recalled all unsold copies from the bookshops, thus turning it into an expensive bibliographical rarity.\"<ref>{{Cite book |first=Theodore |last=Dalrymple |authorlink=Theodore Dalrymple |title=Spoilt Rotten |location=London |publisher=Gibson Square |year=2010 |page=244}}</ref>\n*[[July 31]] \u2013 The [[Attorney General]] of the United Kingdom institutes legal proceedings against London newspaper ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' to prevent it publishing details from the book ''[[Spycatcher]]'' on grounds of security.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/31/newsid_2492000/2492169.stm |title=Newspaper caught in Spycatcher row |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2007-07-02 |date=1987-07-31}}</ref> On September 23, an Australian court lifts the ban on its book publication.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/23/newsid_2528000/2528695.stm |title=Ban lifted on MI5 man's memoirs |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2007-07-02 |date=1987-09-23}}</ref>\n*August \u2013 A new building for the [[National Library of New Zealand]] in [[Wellington]] opens.\n*[[Tom Wolfe]] is paid US $5 million for the film rights to his novel ''[[The Bonfire of the Vanities]]'' (published in book format in October), a record fee to an author at this time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gawker.com/550825/tom-wolfe |work=Gawker |title=Tom Wolfe |accessdate=2012-10-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317194641/http://gawker.com/550825/tom-wolfe |archivedate=2014-03-17}}</ref>\n*[[Ian Rankin]]'s ''[[Knots and Crosses]]'', first of the [[Inspector Rebus]] [[detective novel]]s set around [[Edinburgh]], is published in London.\n\n==New books==\n<!--(''Title of published book translation''), (\"Title of published poem/story translation\"), (literal translation of title)-->\n===Fiction===\n*[[Chinua Achebe]] \u2013 ''[[Anthills of the Savannah]]''\n*[[Peter Ackroyd]] \u2013 ''Chatterton'' (shortlisted for Booker Prize 1987)\n*[[Douglas Adams]] \u2013 ''[[Dirk Gently's Holistic Detective Agency]]''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hahn |first1=Daniel |title=The Oxford Companion to Children's Literature |date=2015 |publisher=Oxford. University Press |isbn=9780198715542 |page=3 |edition=2nd}}</ref>\n*[[Martin Amis]] \u2013 ''[[Einstein's Monsters]]''\n*[[Gilles Archambault]] \u2013 ''L'Obs\u00e9dante ob\u00e8se et autres agressions''\n*[[Paul Auster]]\n**''[[The New York Trilogy]]''\n**''[[In the Country of Last Things]]''\n*[[Iain Banks]]\n**''[[Consider Phlebas]]'' (as Iain M. Banks)\n**''[[Espedair Street]]''\n*[[Clive Barker]] \u2013 ''[[Weaveworld]]''\n*[[Greg Bear]] \u2013 ''[[The Forge of God]]''\n*[[Thomas Berger (novelist)|Thomas Berger]] \u2013 ''Being Invisible''\n*[[William Boyd (writer)|William Boyd]] \u2013 ''[[The New Confessions]]''\n*[[T.C. Boyle]] \u2013 ''[[World's End (Boyle novel)|World's End]]'' (1988 [[PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction]])\n*[[Marion Zimmer Bradley]] \u2013 ''[[The Firebrand]]''\n*[[Truddi Chase]] \u2013 ''[[When Rabbit Howls]]''\n*[[Tom Clancy]] \u2013 ''[[Patriot Games]]''\n*[[Hugh Cook (science fiction author)|Hugh Cook]]\n**''The Wordsmiths and the Warguild''\n**''The Women and the Warlords''\n*[[Robin Cook (novelist)|Robin Cook]] \u2013 ''[[Outbreak (novel)|Outbreak]]''\n*[[Bernard Cornwell]]\n**''Redcoat''\n**''[[Sharpe's Rifles (novel)|Sharpe's Rifles]]''\n*[[Robert Crais]] \u2013 ''[[The Monkey's Raincoat]]''\n*[[L. Sprague de Camp]] and [[Catherine Crook de Camp]] \u2013 ''[[The Incorporated Knight]]''\n*[[Jenny Diski]] \u2013 ''[[Rainforest (novel)|Rainforest]]''\n*[[Jim Dodge]] \u2013 ''Not Fade Away''\n*[[Roddy Doyle]] \u2013 ''[[The Commitments (novel)|The Commitments]]''\n*[[Bret Easton Ellis]] \u2013 ''[[The Rules of Attraction]]''\n*[[James Ellroy]] \u2013 ''[[Black Dahlia]]''\n*[[Carlos Fuentes]] \u2013 ''[[Christopher Unborn]]''\n*[[Neil Gaiman]] and [[Dave McKean]] \u2013 ''[[Violent Cases]]'' (graphic novel)\n*[[John Gardner (thriller writer)|John Gardner]] \u2013 ''[[No Deals, Mr. Bond]]''\n*[[Kaye Gibbons]] \u2013 ''[[Ellen Foster]]''\n*[[Ken Grimwood]] \u2013 ''[[Replay (Grimwood novel)|Replay]]''\n*[[Larry Heinemann]] \u2013 ''[[Paco's Story]]'' (1987 [[National Book Award for Fiction]])\n*[[Tom Holt]] \u2013 ''[[Expecting Someone Taller]]''\n*[[Josephine Humphreys]] \u2013 ''[[Rich in Love]]''\n*[[D\u01b0\u01a1ng Thu H\u01b0\u01a1ng]] \u2013 ''B\u00ean kia b\u1edd \u1ea3o v\u1ecdng'' (Beyond Illusions)\n*[[John Jakes]] \u2013 ''[[Heaven and Hell (Jakes novel)|Heaven and Hell]]''\n*[[Tahar Ben Jelloun]] \u2013 ''La Nuit sacr\u00e9e'' (Th